---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="From the Camera to the Kill Chain">
  <div class="content">
    <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">Learn &middot; 03</span>
    <h1>The Camera Is the Front Door</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 1.15rem;">
      Each piece we've documented is one node of a single architecture. The same kind of company builds the targeting system for the drone and the tracking system for the deportation. Here's how the local camera connects to it.
    </p>

    <h2>Start With the Camera</h2>
    <p>
      The Flock cameras in Safford log every plate, build a Vehicle Fingerprint, and feed a national searchable network. Flock's Nova platform can plug into predictive-policing systems, <strong>including Palantir</strong>. That's the on-ramp.
    </p>

    <h2>Meet Palantir</h2>
    <p>
      Palantir was founded in 2003 with CIA venture funding, and is chaired by billionaire Peter Thiel, a major financial backer of the current administration and mentor to the vice president. It builds the data backbone for two very different operations that turn out to be the same machine.
    </p>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">Deportation</span>
      <h3>ImmigrationOS</h3>
      <p>Palantir's ICE platform, a roughly $30 million contract, pulls together license plates, Medicaid records, and travel data to give the agency "near real-time visibility" into people's movements.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>Assigns a <strong>"confidence score"</strong> for how likely you are to be found at an address</li>
        <li>Drops a <strong>pin on a map</strong> for arrest</li>
        <li>ICE contracts with Palantir total <strong>$435M+ since 2011</strong></li>
        <li>Palantir's tools raised ICE's target-location rate from ~27% to nearly <strong>80%</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="source">Sources: ACLU (Apr 2026); Fortune (Jan 2026); American Immigration Council; AFSC Investigate.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">Targeting</span>
      <h3>Project Maven</h3>
      <p>The same company runs Maven, the Pentagon's AI targeting system, which uses satellite imagery, drone footage, and predictive algorithms to automate the "kill chain": find, fix, track, target, engage.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>The contract grew from <strong>$480 million into the billions</strong></li>
        <li>Pentagon staff used Maven extensively to <strong>pick targets in the US strikes on Iran</strong></li>
        <li>Palantir's CEO: "our weapons software is in every combat situation I'm aware of"</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="source">Sources: Liberation News (June 2025); Davis Vanguard (July 2025); AFSC Investigate.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Same Architecture, Pointed Different Ways</h2>
    <p>
      The plate reader, the dossier, the confidence score, the kill chain. One architecture, built to integrate every database into a single searchable interface. Tested on immigrants and on Palestinians first. The American Immigration Council puts it plainly: when a system decides which data triggers an alert, <strong>the architecture itself becomes policy.</strong>
    </p>

    <h2>And Now There's an Enemies List</h2>
    <p>
      In September 2025 the administration signed <strong>NSPM-7</strong>, a directive that brands "anti-fascism" as a cover for terrorism and lists <strong>"anti-capitalism"</strong> and "anti-Christianity" as indicators of extremism. Not actions. Beliefs. The May 2026 Counterterrorism Strategy went further and named "Anti-Fascists" as a top domestic threat category.
    </p>
    <p>
      Put the surveillance network next to the enemies list. A government that writes "anti-fascist" and "anti-capitalist" into a terror directive, and a camera network that has already logged who drove to a protest. The machine is built and it has already been aimed. How far they take it is the open question.
    </p>
    <p class="source">Sources: White House, "Countering Domestic Terrorism and Organized Political Violence" (Sept 25, 2025); Brennan Center; ACLU; TIME; 2026 U.S. Counterterrorism Strategy.</p>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>The Front Door Is on Your Street</h3>
      <p>You can't unplug Palantir from here. You can ask who's been searching the cameras in Graham County, and you can organize your town the way five Arizona communities already have.</p>
      <a href={`${base}records/`} class="btn">Take Action</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
